node.text: Dating back to the 19th century, the humble pantry box was a smart invention-it’s the ideal receptacle because it’s made of wood, which breathes; it keeps critters out (unless they chew a hole in the side!); and it blocks sunlight. Things that plastic and glass containers don’t do. No surprise that pantry boxes remain one of the most popular primitive collectibles to this day. #countryhomecollected

Hi @countryhomemagazine friends. It’s Hanna here from @homeathand  It’s time to say goodbye, but please stay in touch. You can find me here @homeathand sharing the journey of our home, DIY projects, flower decor and more on a daily basis.
Before I go, I want to share our antique doors used throughout the addition. Each door has its own unique story and history. Most are sourced from our in-laws’ 1910 home in Sweden, and one is from my brother’s rural farmhouse. The vintage doors help us add personality and warmth to our new construction, creating a seamless transition from the original cabin. 
Once again thanks for hanging out with me here at the @countryhomemagazine takeover. It was so much fun and I would love to hear from you. You can find me at @homeathand 
Big hugs and see you soon. Hanna

Hi again. It’s me again Hanna @homeathand⁠⁠
I am a passionate vintage collector, and it all started in my early childhood in rural Sweden, where unique, hand-made furniture is common.  I found our dining table there a couple of years ago while antique hunting. It was made in 1891. The year is engraved underneath by the craftsman that made it.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
One of my favorite things to do is to set our table for a nice dinner.  I do it for fun sometimes, even if it's just our family, and no special occasion. Hop over to Stories to see how our table looks dressed for dinner. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
A fun DIY project can be found in our dining room, where rice paper and spray paint helped revive our dining pendant light adding texture and a personalized touch. This project is saved to a story highlight on my page @homeathand

node.text:
Happy Sunday friends. It’s Hanna @homeathand ⁠⁠
Welcome to stop 4 on my Country Home takeover. Our kitchen is the best part of our new addition. This is where we gather for dinner, do homework and have our afternoon coffee. It is connected to the dining and family room and the big open floor plan makes for a social and lively house. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
When I designed our kitchen, I felt that it was important to add rustic but elegant features that would blend with the original part of our cabin. I wanted the walls to have a warm, refined and  rustic texture, so I painted them with limewash paint. Have you heard about limewash paint? It gives the walls a plaster-like texture.  I have a DIY tutorial on my page @homeathand if you would like to find out more.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
In Stories, you can get the whole kitchen tour. One of my favorite features is the long window seat where we enjoy Swedish “fika”, watch birds, do homework and eat all our meals. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
See you soon in the dining room.

Hi again, Country Home friends. It is me, Hanna @homeathand Welcome inside our cabin! The character of the original log beam construction is what sold us on the house 10 years ago, but this room looked nothing like this. Everything was dated, faded, orange-colored pine. It is amazing how paint and stain can transform a space, don't you think? ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Last July, I was here every morning staining the ceiling, log walls and beams. Join me in stories for the before and after photos, and a movie tour. I can’t believe how different it looks now. We needed to look beyond all the orange pine to see the potential.

node.text:
Hey Country Home friends! I’m Hanna from @homeathand and I am so honored and excited to be your host for the Country Home takeover this weekend. Welcome to our log home here on lake Allatoona, GA. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
It has been exactly one year since we moved back to our house after a big remodel and extension. The cabin was very outdated when we bought it in 2010. We more than doubled the size, and gave it a complete makeover. My goal as the designer was to enhance the cozy and rustic elements while adding a natural and sophisticated Scandinavian touch (I grew up in Sweden). ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
You can find me here @homeathand almost every day sharing our home’s ongoing journey. ⁠⁠DIY projects, food, vintage collecting and flower decor are my favorite subjects. If you like to know how I made our front door wreaths you can hop over to stories. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Making flower arrangements from foraged finds and backyard beauties is so fulfilling. This time I used dried mother’s day roses, backyard hydrangeas and English Ivy from my friend’s house. ⁠⁠
Talk soon! Hanna
